cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 65 miles WSW of St. Petersburg, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: moving north, then turning north-northeast across north-central Florida Thursday and emerging into the western Atlantic, thereafter accelerating northeastward parallel to the Georgia–South Carolina coast
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: the northern portion of the Florida peninsula (near the Big Bend / Cedar Key area)

weather_observation.impacted_coast: Initially the west-central Gulf coast of Florida, then portions of the southeast U.S. coast from northeast Florida through the Carolinas as the system moves offshore
weather_observation.wind: Breezy to gusty conditions (up to near-gale force) possible Friday as Eta passes offshore
weather_observation.storm_surge: None expected for the South Carolina coast
weather_observation.rainfall: Scattered heavy showers possible Friday with generally light to moderate totals (<4 in.)
weather_observation.other_hazards: Rough seas and dangerous rip currents along the South Carolina coast Friday–Saturday
